[2026-03-13T14:41:40Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DYUGkaDmeivE9DdDR2ug9Z","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Now I have thoroughly explored the codebase. Let me compile my findings:\n\n## Security-Relevant Implementation Details in Cloche\n\nBased on a comprehensive exploration of the Cloche codebase, here are all the safety-relevant implementation details:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Container Network Configuration\n\n**Location**: `/workspace/internal/adapters/docker/runtime.go` (lines 77, 162) and `/workspace/internal/ports/container.go` (lines 19)\n\n**Current Status**: \n- The `ContainerConfig` struct has a `NetworkAllow []string` field defined\n- **However, network allowlisting is NOT implemented in the Docker runtime**\n- The field is parsed from the DSL (`container { network_allow = [...] }`)\n- In actual execution, `NetworkAllow` is hardcoded to `[\"*\"]` in `/workspace/internal/adapters/grpc/server.go` (line 162)\n- No firewall, DNS, or network filtering logic exists in the codebase\n- Comment at line 77 of runtime.go explicitly states: \"No --network none: agent needs network for git push and API access\"\n\n**Important Gap**: While the DSL supports declaring `network_allow`, this is purely documentation - it is not enforced at runtime.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Host-Side Prompt Handling\n\n**Location**: `/workspace/internal/host/executor.go` and `/workspace/internal/adapters/agents/prompt/prompt.go`\n\n**Implementation**:\n- Prompts are prepared in two ways:\n  1. **Script-based preparation**: Host scripts (e.g., `.cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh`) can sanitize/validate user input before writing to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`\n  2. **Agent-based preparation**: Host-side agent steps run with full daemon privileges\n- Prompts are written to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt` before being passed to containers\n- The prompt assembler (`assemblePrompt` in prompt.go lines 361-399) concatenates:\n  1. System template (from `prompt` field in DSL)\n  2. User prompt (from `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt`)\n  3. Optional feedback logs (if `feedback = \"true\"`)\n  4. Result selection instructions\n\n**Security Note**: The architecture encourages script-based preparation on the host (safer) rather than agent-based (less safe, has full privileges).\n\n---\n\n### 3. Container Isolation (File Copying Model)\n\n**Location**: `/workspace/internal/adapters/docker/runtime.go` (lines 107-128) and `/workspace/internal/adapters/docker/extract.go`\n\n**Implementation**:\n- **Copy-based isolation (not bind mounts)**:\n  - Project files are copied from host into container using `docker cp` (line 109)\n  - `.cloche/overrides/` files are applied on top via `docker cp` (line 121)\n  - Claude auth files (`~/.claude`, `~/.claude.json`) are copied individually per container to avoid concurrent write conflicts (lines 131-140)\n- **Container setup**:\n  - Default user is `agent` (unprivileged)\n  - Workspace is owned by `agent:agent`\n  - Serena MCP tools are removed from container to avoid wasting agent time (line 85)\n  - Settings plugin enablement is stripped from Claude config (line 87)\n- **Results extraction**:\n  - Container output is copied back via `docker cp` to a temporary directory\n  - Results are committed to git worktrees, not directly to the main branch\n  - The container's `.git` directory is explicitly removed to avoid overwriting the worktree's `.git` file pointer (line 55)\n\n---\n\n### 4. Workflow DSL Security\n\n**Location**: `/workspace/internal/domain/workflow.go`, `/workspace/internal/dsl/parser.go`\n\n**Validation**:\n- Workflow location checking: `ValidateLocation()` ensures `workflow_name` steps only appear in host.cloche (lines 233-242)\n- Graph validation: All declared step results must be wired; no orphaned steps (Validate method, lines 145-229)\n- Output mapping validation: Duplicate env var mappings targeting the same step are rejected (lines 214-226)\n- Config key validation: Unknown configuration keys trigger warnings (ValidateConfig, lines 259-276)\n- JSON path evaluation: Output mappings safely navigate JSON with bounds checking (OutputPath.Evaluate, lines 75-115)\n\n**No explicit permission system**: The DSL has no fine-grained access controls. Steps are either allowed or not.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Network Allowlisting (Attempted but Not Enforced)\n\n**Location**: `/workspace/docs/SAFETY.md` (lines 72-126), `/workspace/internal/dsl/parser_test.go` (line 82, 94)\n\n**Status**: \n- The DSL supports declaring `network_allow = [\"domain.com\", ...]`\n- **NOT IMPLEMENTED in runtime** - no code enforces these restrictions\n- The SAFETY.md document recommends:\n  - Whitelisting only essential domains (AI provider API, git remote, package registries)\n  - Using Docker-level controls (dependency baking into images, DNS restrictions)\n  - Building all dependencies at Docker build time to eliminate runtime network needs\n- **Key insight**: Cloche relies on users to implement network restriction via Dockerfile best practices, not via Cloche itself\n\n---\n\n### 6. Agent Adapter Security\n\n**Location**: `/workspace/internal/ports/agent.go`, `/workspace/internal/adapters/agents/prompt/prompt.go`, `/workspace/cmd/cloche-agent/main.go`\n\n**Agent Adapters**:\n- **Prompt Adapter** (prompt.go): Invokes `claude` CLI command with arguments; supports fallback chain\n  - Default args for Claude: `[\"-p\", \"--output-format\", \"stream-json\", \"--verbose\", \"--dangerously-skip-permissions\"]`\n  - Prompts are passed via stdin\n  - Output is captured and classified for result markers\n- **Generic Adapter**: Runs arbitrary shell commands\n- **No sandboxing within the container**: Agents run as the `agent` user with full container filesystem access\n\n**Environment Variables**:\n- `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` is passed into containers and unset before executing the agent (main.go, lines 32-33)\n- `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` is passed through if set in host environment (docker/runtime.go, lines 52-53)\n- Agents inherit the container's full environment\n\n---\n\n### 7. Existing Security Documentation\n\n**Location**: `/workspace/docs/SAFETY.md` (comprehensive 219-line safety guide)\n\n**Key Topics Covered**:\n1. **The Lethal Trifecta**: Access to private data + exposure to untrusted content + external communication = vulnerability\n2. **Host-side minimization**: Host workflows run with daemon privileges; prefer container workflows\n3. **Network allowlisting**: Recommended practice (not enforced)\n4. **Filesystem isolation**: Copy-based model prevents direct host modification\n5. **Credential handling**:\n   - `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` automatically passed into containers\n   - Other env vars require explicit `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV`\n   - Claude auth files copied per-container\n   - Do not bake secrets into Dockerfiles\n6. **Prompt hygiene**: Separate trusted templates from untrusted user input; sanitize in script steps\n7. **Review before merge**: All agent changes should be reviewed as branches before merging\n\n---\n\n### 8. Critical Security Implementation Details\n\n**Credential Handling** (`/workspace/internal/adapters/docker/runtime.go`):\n- `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` is passed as env var only if set in host (line 52-53)\n- Claude auth files are copied (not mounted) to each container individually (lines 131-140)\n- Support for `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS` and `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` for additional configuration (lines 59-75)\n- **Warning**: Users must be careful with `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS` to avoid exposing sensitive host directories\n\n**User Permissions** (`/workspace/internal/adapters/docker/runtime.go`):\n- Container runs as unprivileged `agent` user by default\n- Workspace directory is owned by `agent:agent` to prevent privilege escalation\n- No `--privileged` flag or capabilities added\n\n**Prompt Injection Surface** (`/workspace/internal/adapters/agents/prompt/prompt.go`):\n- User prompt is read from `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt` (lines 452-461)\n- Untrusted content can be included in feedback logs via `feedback = \"true\"` (lines 415-439)\n- **Recommendation**: Script steps should validate/sanitize user input before writing prompt\n\n---\n\n### Summary of Security Gaps and Notes\n\n1. **Network allowlisting is declared but not enforced** - users must rely on Dockerfile best practices\n2. **Host-side workflows run with full daemon privileges** - architecture is designed to encourage container workflows instead\n3. **No fine-grained access control in DSL** - all steps or nothing\n4. **No image signature verification** - containers pulled/built without verification\n5. **Output mappings can include untrusted data** - feedback logs are included if enabled\n6. **Results extraction via git** - provides review checkpoint but no automated validation\n\n**Strengths**:\n- Copy-based filesystem isolation (prevents direct host fs modification)\n- Unprivileged container user by default\n- Per-container credential copies (prevents concurrent write conflicts)\n- Comprehensive safety documentation with practical recommendations\n- Location-based workflow validation (host vs container)\n\n---\n\n### Key Files for Reference\n\n- **Safety Guide**: `/workspace/docs/SAFETY.md`\n- **Docker Runtime**: `/workspace/internal/adapters/docker/runtime.go`\n- **Extract Results**: `/workspace/internal/adapters/docker/extract.go`\n- **Container Ports**: `/workspace/internal/ports/container.go`\n- **Agent Prompt Adapter**: `/workspace/internal/adapters/agents/prompt/prompt.go`\n- **Host Executor**: `/workspace/internal/host/executor.go`\n- **Workflow Domain**: `/workspace/internal/domain/workflow.go`\n- **Base Dockerfile**: `/workspace/docker/cloche-base/Dockerfile`\n- **DSL Parser**: `/workspace/internal/dsl/parser.go`"},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: aa0f989952167f37e (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 71885\ntool_uses: 46\nduration_ms: 182405</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d